<br>
I wish to share with you a tale of the heroic exploits of my brother paladin, Sir Kronenburg Ponykeg.  Two days ago, Lord Adlehardt, Lady Nalena and I ventured forth into the very depths of Castle Mistmoore, seeking the elusive Mistmoore granite and black cauldrons I need obtain to be granted the Armor of Ro. <br>
<br>
After my companions mounted a valiant and ferocious assault on the malignant ancile cooks in Mistmoore’s kitchen, countless fierce gargoyles assaulted us as we made our way from the castle.  Although Lord Adlehardt fought with lupine bravery to protect us while Lady Nalena extracted a heavy blood price from our foes, we fell beneath their onslaught, leaving our equipment deep within the heart of Mistmoore.<br>
<br>
Later, Lord Adlehardt applied his many druidic arts in an attempt to retrieve our belongings from the castle, but the vile sorceresses allied with our dark enemies countered his every attempt to venture within unseen.  Our situation looked quite grim.  <br>
<br>
Enter our very own Sir Kronenburg Ponykeg.  Where arcane art failed, his strong arm and boundless courage prevailed.  With great risk to his person – stalked by the most harrowing of foes at every turn – Sir Kronenburg mounted a single-handed, frontal assault on our foes.  Swinging his great axe as he struggled forth, thrice he assaulted the castle to drag his fallen comrades from harm’s way, leaving a trail of his own blood and countless fallen enemies in his wake.  <br>
<br>
As a paladin, I pray to Tunare that She may grant my sword arm the strength and my heart the courage to conduct myself as he did that day, should you, my brothers and sisters, ever have need of me.  Though small of stature, Sir Kronenburg towers above me in his fearlessness and devotion to service.  I hail him as a shining example of valor, perseverance, and service.<br>
<br>
<br>
Lyri Prayerblade<br>
Paladin of Tunare<br>
